<subSubSection id="C367657D472DC957674FF9421D0C9A0C" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC236F6472DC957674FF9421D0C9A0C" blockId="1.[264,1323,1784,1890]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="B909EAE4472DC957674FF94219A09A7F" box="[264,389,1784,1809]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">Etymology</emphasis>
The species name is in reference to Monte Sano, which is Spanish for &quot;mountain of health.&quot; The common name, Sano snowfly, is proposed for this species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B07472DC9576212F8F21D399A0C" author="Stark, B. P. &amp; Stewart, K. W. &amp; Szczytko, S. W. &amp; Baumann, R. W." box="[1109,1308,1864,1890]" pageId="1" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref2074" refString="Stark, B. P., Stewart, K. W., Szczytko, S. W. &amp; Baumann, R. W. (1998) Common names of stoneflies (Plecoptera) from the United States and Canada. Ohio Biological Survey Notes, 1, 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="1998">
Stark 
<emphasis id="B909EAE4472DC95762DCF8F21CEB9A0F" box="[1179,1230,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="40">et al</emphasis>
. 1998
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
